  - STATE_UPDATE: {'solution_plan': '[HYBRID]: Strategy guided by General Principles of shell script variable initialization and library linking, but implementation details are derived from code analysis of the OSS-Fuzz integration and previous failure patterns.\n\nThe fix addresses both the shell script regression and the AFL linking issue:\n\n1. **Fixed `build.sh`**: \n   - Added proper initialization of `LDFLAGS` variable using `[ -z "${LDFLAGS+x}" ]` check\n   - This prevents "unbound variable" error when `LDFLAGS` is not previously set\n   - Maintains AFL++ library linking flags for Bazel\n\n2. **Enhanced `repository.bzl`**:\n   - Added detection of AFL++ engine via `FUZZING_ENGINE` environment variable\n   - Added AFL++ library linking (`-L/src/aflplusplus -lAFLDriver -lAFLQemuDriver`) when:\n     - `LIB_FUZZING_ENGINE` is a flag (like `-lAFLDriver`) AND `FUZZING_ENGINE=afl`\n     - `LIB_FUZZING_ENGINE` is an archive (`.a` file) AND `FUZZING_ENGINE=afl`\n     - Even if `LIB_FUZZING_ENGINE` is not set but `FUZZING_ENGINE=afl`\n   - This ensures the `oss_fuzz_engine.a` archive\'s AFL++ driver symbols are properly linked\n\n3. **Updated `BUILD.tpl`**:\n   - Added `alwayslink = 1` to ensure AFL++ driver symbols in the archive are always linked\n   - This is crucial for archives that contain object files with undefined symbols\n\nThe key insight is that the `oss_fuzz_engine.a` archive contains the AFL++ driver object file (`aflpp_driver.o`) which references AFL++ symbols. These symbols need to be resolved by linking with the AFL++ libraries (`libAFLDriver.a`, `libAFLQemuDriver.a`). The fix ensures this linking happens at multiple levels:\n- Shell script level (for general build environment)\n- Bazel repository rule level (for OSS-Fuzz engine configuration)\n- Bazel target level (via `alwayslink = 1`)\n\nThis approach addresses the regression from attempt 5 while solving the original AFL linking issue.'}
