 AFL++ runtime library\n2. **Reality**: It's just a stub that expects the real runtime to be present\n3. **Limitation**: No amount of linker flag configuration can fix missing runtime libraries\n\n## NEW STRATEGY REQUIRED\nWe need to switch from **Strategy A (Config Repair)** to a different approach:\n\n### STRATEGY B: Find Missing AFL++ Runtime\nSearch for the actual AFL++ runtime library in the container:\n```bash\nfind /src -name \"*AFL*\" -type f -exec file {} \\;\nfind /usr -name \"*AFL*\" -type f 2>/dev/null\nls -la /src/aflplusplus/\n```\n\n### STRATEGY C: Install Missing AFL++ Runtime\nIf the runtime is missing, install it:\n```bash\napt-get update && apt-get install -y afl++ afl++-clang\n```\n\n### STRATEGY D: Switch to Different Fuzzing Engine\nIf AFL++ runtime cannot be found/installed, switch to a different engine:\n- **libfuzzer**: Already supported by the project\n- **honggfuzz**: Also supported\n- Modify build.sh to use a different engine when AFL fails\n\n### STRATEGY E: Patch the OSS-Fuzz Engine Configuration\nModify the `@rules_fuzzing_oss_fuzz//:oss_fuzz_engine` target to work without AFL++ runtime:\n- Create a custom engine that doesn't depend on AFL symbols\n- Or modify the existing engine to use a different linking approach\n\n## COMMIT ANALYSIS INSIGHT\nThe commit `1b9ddac66217c77f4eea0d3a8b765953ab5080b5` \"Add aliases for OSS-Fuzz engines (#258)\" changed how OSS-Fuzz engines are referenced. This might have introduced a dependency issue where the engine configuration assumes AFL++ runtime is available.\n\n## PRIORITY RECOMMENDATIONS\n1. **First**: Search for existing AFL++ runtime libraries in the container\n2. **Second**: If not found, try to install AFL++ runtime\n3. **Third**: If installation fails, switch to libfuzzer engine\n4. **Fourth**: Consider patching the OSS-Fuzz engine configuration\n\n## DIAGNOSTIC COMMANDS\n1. Search for AFL libraries: `find /src /usr -name \"*AFL*\" -type f 2>/dev/null`\n2. Check what AFL packages are installed: `dpkg -l | grep -i afl`\n3. Test if AFL++ compiler works: `afl-clang-fast --version`\n4. Check OSS-Fuzz engine configuration: Examine `@rules_fuzzing_oss_fuzz//:oss_fuzz_engine` target\n\n## CONTEXTUAL NOTES\n- This is a **post-rollback** state - we've reverted all config changes\n- Strategy A was exhausted (3 attempts without success)\n- We have a clearer understanding of the problem: missing AFL++ runtime\n- The project supports multiple fuzzing engines (libfuzzer, afl, honggfuzz)\n- Switching to libfuzzer might be the simplest fix given the incomplete AFL++ installation"})
